00:11:58,850 --> 00:12:02,750
AUDIENCE: There's a line like
[INAUDIBLE] it's saying hi.

247
00:12:02,750 --> 00:12:04,048
The circle is saying hi.

248
00:12:04,048 --> 00:12:05,590
DAVID MALAN: The circle is saying hi.

249
00:12:05,590 --> 00:12:09,290


250
00:12:09,290 --> 00:12:11,716
Not wrong, but OK.

251
00:12:11,716 --> 00:12:18,150
AUDIENCE: You start from the
bottom of the circle [INAUDIBLE] Y.

252
00:12:18,150 --> 00:12:21,150
DAVID MALAN: Start from the bottom
of the circle and draw an upside down

253
00:12:21,150 --> 00:12:24,990
Y. OK, nice.

254
00:12:24,990 --> 00:12:25,490
Yeah.

255
00:12:25,490 --> 00:12:26,910
OK, another step.

256
00:12:26,910 --> 00:12:27,480
Shout it out.

257
00:12:27,480 --> 00:12:28,177
Yeah.

258
00:12:28,177 --> 00:12:29,310
AUDIENCE: Draw some arms.

259
00:12:29,310 --> 00:12:31,060
DAVID MALAN: Draw some arms.

260
00:12:31,060 --> 00:12:34,080
[LAUGHTER]

261
00:12:34,080 --> 00:12:35,890
OK.

262
00:12:35,890 --> 00:12:37,116
Other instructions?

263
00:12:37,116 --> 00:12:39,760


264
00:12:39,760 --> 00:12:40,890
Yeah.

265
00:12:40,890 --> 00:12:43,390
AUDIENCE: Draw a line
from the circle to hi.

266
00:12:43,390 --> 00:12:46,480
DAVID MALAN: Draw a line
from the circle to hi.

267
00:12:46,480 --> 00:12:50,560
And albeit with some artistic liberties,
I think that's pretty darn close.

268
00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:52,545
Do you want to look up finally?

269
00:12:52,545 --> 00:12:54,710
And a round of applause here.

270
00:12:54,710 --> 00:12:55,910
[APPLAUSE]

271
00:12:55,910 --> 00:12:56,410
Thank you.

272
00:12:56,410 --> 00:12:57,850
Very nicely done.

273
00:12:57,850 --> 00:12:58,550
Thank you.

274
00:12:58,550 --> 00:13:01,450
So here, too, that was actually
extraordinarily well done

275
00:13:01,450 --> 00:13:03,200
for the instructions that were given.

276
00:13:03,200 --> 00:13:06,328
So the hi, of course, is
off to the wrong side.

277
00:13:06,328 --> 00:13:08,870
But this, too, sort of speaks
to the importance of precision.

278
00:13:08,870 --> 00:13:11,560
It's not just enough to say
that the circle is saying hi.

279
00:13:11,560 --> 00:13:14,540
Probably should have specified
top left versus some other angle.

280
00:13:14,540 --> 00:13:16,690
And instead of, if I
may, draw arms, we could

281
00:13:16,690 --> 00:13:20,500
have been a little more specific as to
the shapes or the angles of the arms

282
00:13:20,500 --> 00:13:21,740
that we wanted to draw.

283
00:13:21,740 --> 00:13:26,360
But of course, once you have implemented
this solution to this problem,

284
00:13:26,360 --> 00:13:29,450
drawing a stick figure, now
you can abstract it away,

285
00:13:29,450 --> 00:13:31,910
put it into your tool
kit, call it a function.

286
00:13:31,910 --> 00:13:35,480
And maybe that function in the future
has certain parameters or inputs

287
00:13:35,480 --> 00:13:40,100
we can pass in that specify the angles
and the size and the word and so forth.

288
00:13:40,100 --> 00:13:42,020
And again, that brings
us back to abstraction,

289
00:13:42,020 --> 00:13:45,660
being able to take something that first
has to be done at a fairly low level,

290
00:13:45,660 --> 00:13:49,400
but then all of us can build on
top of that idea again and again

291
00:13:49,400 --> 00:13:55,280
and hopefully, avoid ever having to
solve precisely that same problem again.

292
00:13:55,280 --> 00:13:57,540
I will review all of
these later, if I may.

293
00:13:57,540 --> 00:14:02,670
So that then is maybe our first
activity in computational thinking.

294
00:14:02,670 --> 00:14:04,770
But we did so much more
this semester as well.

295
00:14:04,770 --> 00:14:07,410
And in fact, if you think
back from this week backwards,

296
00:14:07,410 --> 00:14:10,640
we started, of course, with Scratch,
this graphical language for dragging

297
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:12,482
and dropping puzzle pieces.

298
00:14:12,482 --> 00:14:14,690
And some of you had played
with that in middle school

299
00:14:14,690 --> 00:14:16,710
or high school or sort
of dabbled just for fun.

300
00:14:16,710 --> 00:14:18,715
But the goal of Scratch
wasn't so much Scratch,

301
00:14:18,715 --> 00:14:20,840
but to introduce some of
those fundamental concepts

302
00:14:20,840 --> 00:14:24,020
that you see in a lot of programming
languages, functions, and arguments,

303
00:14:24,020 --> 00:14:27,960
and return values, conditionals,
loops, variables, and more.

304
00:14:27,960 --> 00:14:31,400
And it gave us this very comfortable
place to experiment with those ideas

305
00:14:31,400 --> 00:14:35,510
and to really hammer home the point
that once things escalated quickly

306
00:14:35,510 --> 00:14:39,500
in week one and we got to see in
more traditional syntax still just

307
00:14:39,500 --> 00:14:41,810
the same ideas, but just a
lot of annoying parentheses,

308
00:14:41,810 --> 00:14:44,720
and semicolons, and quotation
marks, and sort of distractions

309
00:14:44,720 --> 00:14:48,195
that hopefully by now you appreciate
is not what programming is about.

310
00:14:48,195 --> 00:14:50,070
It's not the intellectually
interesting part.

311
00:14:50,070 --> 00:14:53,270
It's just the annoying aspect
of learning some new language

312
00:14:53,270 --> 00:14:57,170
and understanding what that new grammar,
that new syntax, that new vocabulary

313
00:14:57,170 --> 00:14:58,230
actually is.

314
00:14:58,230 --> 00:15:02,330
Thereafter, we began to explore how
you can solve problems in memory.

315
00:15:02,330 --> 00:15:05,300
We talked about arrays as
really the first sort of way

316
00:15:05,300 --> 00:15:09,110
to represent or to store
information readily in memory

317
00:15:09,110 --> 00:15:12,323
and solve problems like keeping
track of multiple values at once.

318
00:15:12,323 --> 00:15:14,240
We then took a step back
from code and focused

319
00:15:14,240 --> 00:15:16,962
on algorithms, step-by-step
instructions for solving problems

320
00:15:16,962 --> 00:15:19,920
for searching and sorting, and a lot
of problems that, though we chose,

321
00:15:19,920 --> 00:15:23,510
simple versions thereof are
really omnipresent in the Googles,

322
00:15:23,510 --> 00:15:25,760
and the Microsofts, the
ChatGPTs of the world

323
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:29,670
that are constantly navigating
super large data sets nowadays.

324
00:15:29,670 --> 00:15:32,760
We talked at the lowest level
about memory and pointers.

325
00:15:32,760 --> 00:15:35,900
And rest assured that in almost
any subsequent programming

326
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:39,540
language you learn, odds are you're
building on top of those ideas,

327
00:15:39,540 --> 00:15:41,250
instead of taking a deeper dive.

328
00:15:41,250 --> 00:15:44,300
Those of you destined to major or
concentrate in computer science

329
00:15:44,300 --> 00:15:48,540
might dabble at that same lower level,
especially if you like that there world.

330
00:15:48,540 --> 00:15:52,160
But then data structures is really what
characterizes a lot of computer science

331
00:15:52,160 --> 00:15:54,890
and all of those trees,
and tries, and hash tables,

332
00:15:54,890 --> 00:15:59,450
and just using this canvas of memory
to create things that only exist

333
00:15:59,450 --> 00:16:01,480
sort of in memory and in our minds.

334
00:16:01,480 --> 00:16:03,980
But if we draw pictures of them,
they really do come to life

335
00:16:03,980 --> 00:16:06,600
and solve problems all
the more efficiently.

336
00:16:06,600 --> 00:16:10,140
Then why Python, why SQL, why all
of these more recent web languages?

337
00:16:10,140 --> 00:16:13,220
Well, Python is much more
useful in a lot of cases than C.

338
00:16:13,220 --> 00:16:17,420
In fact, personally, I only use
C between September and October

339
00:16:17,420 --> 00:16:17,990
of each year.

340
00:16:17,990 --> 00:16:19,610
And then I sort of have to
relearn it the next year

341
00:16:19,610 --> 00:16:21,193
because I just don't use it that much.

342
00:16:21,193 --> 00:16:23,670
It's still incredibly
popular and omnipresent,

343
00:16:23,670 --> 00:16:28,010
but for fairly low-level applications,
where performance and speed and memory

344
00:16:28,010 --> 00:16:29,970
are really precious and important.

345
00:16:29,970 --> 00:16:33,120
But most of us, when we start
solving problems with code,

346
00:16:33,120 --> 00:16:35,660
are probably going to reach
for something like Python or R

347
00:16:35,660 --> 00:16:38,900
or Java or some higher level
language, like JavaScript

348
00:16:38,900 --> 00:16:42,740
as well, just because it's easier
to solve common problems with those

349
00:16:42,740 --> 00:16:43,770
there languages.

350
00:16:43,770 --> 00:16:46,640
SQL though, in particular, was
a different type of language.

351
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:48,770
And it let us talk about
something we might now

352
00:16:48,770 --> 00:16:51,740
know as declarative programming,
where it doesn't really

353
00:16:51,740 --> 00:16:54,870
matter how you get the
data or how you select it,

354
00:16:54,870 --> 00:16:57,260
but just that you want
to select some data,

355
00:16:57,260 --> 00:16:59,520
and this is the type of
data you want to select.

356
00:16:59,520 --> 00:17:02,630
And there's no more loops and
variables and conditionals.

357
00:17:02,630 --> 00:17:05,520
The language just takes
care of all of that for you.

358
00:17:05,520 --> 00:17:09,530
And then, of course, there's the web,
HTML, CSS, throw in some JavaScript.

359
00:17:09,530 --> 00:17:13,190
This is what most every application
with which we are familiar every day

360
00:17:13,190 --> 00:17:16,650
nowadays uses for the web,
for mobile devices as well.

361
00:17:16,650 --> 00:17:20,310
But there too, once we got to
JavaScript, if briefly, we explored,

362
00:17:20,310 --> 00:17:23,450
we revisited those same ideas,
functions, conditionals, loops,

363
00:17:23,450 --> 00:17:24,625
again and again.

364
00:17:24,625 --> 00:17:27,000
Now, this isn't the entirety
of the world of programming.

365
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:29,400
There are other types
of languages out there.

366
00:17:29,400 --> 00:17:30,770
SQL hints at this.

367
00:17:30,770 --> 00:17:32,250
Python hints of this.

368
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:35,310
Besides declarative programming,
there's functional programming,

369
00:17:35,310 --> 00:17:36,960
object oriented programming.

370
00:17:36,960 --> 00:17:38,970
And there's still
therefore, much to learn.

371
00:17:38,970 --> 00:17:41,420
But we focus in CS50 on
procedural programming,

372
00:17:41,420 --> 00:17:45,980
step by step truly instructions
for solving problems in code.

373
00:17:45,980 --> 00:17:48,050
But there's even more
out there to learn.

374
00:17:48,050 --> 00:17:50,262
And indeed, when we end
the course here with Flask,

375
00:17:50,262 --> 00:17:51,970
the motivation there
in particular is not

376
00:17:51,970 --> 00:17:55,400
to teach some library or framework
because those are a dime a dozen,

377
00:17:55,400 --> 00:17:57,970
but to choose a simple
one, so that you can really

378
00:17:57,970 --> 00:18:02,860
explore the confluence of a lot of these
ideas in your very own last problem set

379
00:18:02,860 --> 00:18:07,010
and ultimately, final project, which
of course, brings us now to week 10.

380
00:18:07,010 --> 00:18:09,520
So the final project really is
meant to be this opportunity

381
00:18:09,520 --> 00:18:12,460
to take your newfound knowledge of
programming and CS out for a spin

382
00:18:12,460 --> 00:18:15,400
and build something of
importance or of interest to you

383
00:18:15,400 --> 00:18:19,670
without being handed a specification
and told exactly what to do.

384
00:18:19,670 --> 00:18:22,330
And you will find that
this too is challenging.

385
00:18:22,330 --> 00:18:25,090
And you will find that you're
Googling and ChatGPTing, which

386
00:18:25,090 --> 00:18:28,090
for this stage of the class
is now welcome and encouraged

387
00:18:28,090 --> 00:18:31,690
because a lot of computer science,
a lot of programming, in particular,

388
00:18:31,690 --> 00:18:35,120
is about just learning new things,
some new functions, some new APIs,

389
00:18:35,120 --> 00:18:36,350
some new library or the like.

390
00:18:36,350 --> 00:18:37,918
That's never going to stop.

391
00:18:37,918 --> 00:18:39,460
But you're going to get better at it.

392
00:18:39,460 --> 00:18:41,418
And you're going to have
all the more instincts

393
00:18:41,418 --> 00:18:44,285
for how to read the
documentation, how to recognize

394
00:18:44,285 --> 00:18:46,670
that, oh, this language
I'm now just learning

395
00:18:46,670 --> 00:18:49,047
is actually pretty similar to
this other thing I learned.

396
00:18:49,047 --> 00:18:52,130
And in fact, if the best thing we
hopefully have done in the class for you

397
00:18:52,130 --> 00:18:56,720
ultimately is just to teach you how
to teach yourself new things, because

398
00:18:56,720 --> 00:19:00,473
in a few weeks' time, poof, we're all
going to disappear from the stage here.

399
00:19:00,473 --> 00:19:03,140
But you'll still have some problems
presumably in the real world

400
00:19:03,140 --> 00:19:05,600
to solve with code or otherwise.

401
00:19:05,600 --> 00:19:08,348
This is the tagline
from the specification.

402
00:19:08,348 --> 00:19:10,640
All that we ask is that you
build something of interest

403
00:19:10,640 --> 00:19:13,370
to you, that you solve an actual
problem, that you impact campus,

404
00:19:13,370 --> 00:19:14,700
or that you change the world.

405
00:19:14,700 --> 00:19:15,480
No pressure.

406
00:19:15,480 --> 00:19:17,565
But ultimately, you
strive to create something

407
00:19:17,565 --> 00:19:20,190
that outlives this course, whether
it's for your student group,

408
00:19:20,190 --> 00:19:21,900
your personal life,
your professional life,

409
00:19:21,900 --> 00:19:24,150
just some proof of concept
you've wanted to play with.

410
00:19:24,150 --> 00:19:26,450
The final project capstone is your own.

411
00:19:26,450 --> 00:19:31,230
And to get you there, we have this
tradition of the CS50 Hackathon,

412
00:19:31,230 --> 00:19:33,690
which will be starting at
7:00 PM later this week,

413
00:19:33,690 --> 00:19:35,210
ending at 7:00 AM the next night.

414
00:19:35,210 --> 00:19:38,190
It's meant to be one of these
memorable collegiate experiences,

415
00:19:38,190 --> 00:19:40,580
academic more so in
nature, that is really

416
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:44,150
meant to be an opportunity alongside
classmates and staff and friends

417
00:19:44,150 --> 00:19:48,120
to collaborate on or struggle your way
through some problem you want to solve.

418
00:19:48,120 --> 00:19:51,170
Here, for instance, are some
visuals from the most recent year.

419
00:19:51,170 --> 00:19:54,060
A certain CS50 duck will
await you to greet you.

420
00:19:54,060 --> 00:19:57,500
But it really is just meant to
be an evening and early morning

421
00:19:57,500 --> 00:20:00,680
of solving problems, writing code,
figuring things out, getting a jumpstart

422
00:20:00,680 --> 00:20:02,120
on your same problem set.

423
00:20:02,120 --> 00:20:04,520
Around 9:00 PM will
first dinner be served.

424
00:20:04,520 --> 00:20:06,810
Around 1:00 AM will
second dinner be served.

425
00:20:06,810 --> 00:20:09,120
And if you still have the
energy around 5:00 AM,

426
00:20:09,120 --> 00:20:13,100
we'll hop in some CS50 shuttles and
head down the street to IHOP as well

427
00:20:13,100 --> 00:20:14,460
for pancakes in the morning.

428
00:20:14,460 --> 00:20:18,680
So if your schedule allows, do join
us for this particular tradition

429
00:20:18,680 --> 00:20:20,130
in a few days' time.

430
00:20:20,130 --> 00:20:23,340
The CS50 Fair, meanwhile,
after Thanksgiving break,

431
00:20:23,340 --> 00:20:26,060
will be this opportunity to
showcase the work that you

432
00:20:26,060 --> 00:20:29,720
create via the final project for
classmates and staff and faculty

433
00:20:29,720 --> 00:20:30,990
across campus.

434
00:20:30,990 --> 00:20:34,760
You'll gather here in a space on
campus where some balloons and music

435
00:20:34,760 --> 00:20:36,300
and food and others will await.

436
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:40,250
And it'll be an opportunity to take
delight in the projects that each of you

437
00:20:40,250 --> 00:20:44,210
have created over these past several
weeks, exhibiting for the world

438
00:20:44,210 --> 00:20:47,510
to see what it is that you accomplished
and more importantly, learned

439
00:20:47,510 --> 00:20:48,590
along the way.

440
00:20:48,590 --> 00:20:51,090
The CS50 duck even lost
his head, so to speak,

441
00:20:51,090 --> 00:20:53,490
last year, was so
impressed by this project.

442
00:20:53,490 --> 00:20:57,330
So too will you meet Varun perhaps
in that their costume as well.

443
00:20:57,330 --> 00:21:00,540
And ultimately, will you receive,
as have all of your predecessors

444
00:21:00,540 --> 00:21:03,890
past, your very own,
I took CS50, t-shirt

445
00:21:03,890 --> 00:21:08,280
that hopefully you can wear proudly
beyond the end of the course itself.

446
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:11,340
So that brings us now
to our second game,

447
00:21:11,340 --> 00:21:15,500
another opportunity to test just
how much has sunk in from that fire

448
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:17,040
