1225
00:53:37,123 --> 00:53:40,280


1226
00:53:40,280 --> 00:53:42,510
Linked list over array.

1227
00:53:42,510 --> 00:53:43,250
Interesting.

1228
00:53:43,250 --> 00:53:45,920
All right, so only
70%, but I think we've

1229
00:53:45,920 --> 00:53:48,890
gotten every question right
by a majority at least,

1230
00:53:48,890 --> 00:53:52,417
is indeed, if we want to
reveal the correct answer.

1231
00:53:52,417 --> 00:53:54,750
So linked lists are advantageous
because you can insert.

1232
00:53:54,750 --> 00:53:55,375
You can remove.

1233
00:53:55,375 --> 00:53:58,250
And you don't have to worry about
moving everything around in memory,

1234
00:53:58,250 --> 00:53:59,455
like you would for an array.

1235
00:53:59,455 --> 00:54:01,830
They don't really give faster
access to elements, though,

1236
00:54:01,830 --> 00:54:04,350
because you lose binary search,
at least as we discussed,

1237
00:54:04,350 --> 00:54:07,700
because you don't have random
access to any of the nodes directly.

1238
00:54:07,700 --> 00:54:11,598
Easier to sort, not really
because there's so much more work

1239
00:54:11,598 --> 00:54:13,140
to do back and forth, back and forth.

1240
00:54:13,140 --> 00:54:16,520
Whereas, with arrays, you can just
swap things using their indices.

1241
00:54:16,520 --> 00:54:18,660
Less memory is used,
your opposite is true.

1242
00:54:18,660 --> 00:54:22,590
You're using more memory, like an extra
space for all of those pointers as well.

